Let’s be real: Ethereum is powerful, but it ain’t cheap. If you’ve ever written a Solidity contract and watched it burn gas faster than a Lamborghini in sport mode, this one’s for you. Whether you're minting NFTs, building DeFi protocols, gas optimization is the secret sauce to saving your users (and yourself) from unnecessary costs. Here are gas-saving tips every Ethereum developer should know in 2025 explained simply, with zero fluff. 1. Use uint256 by Default (and Consistently) uint8 or uint32 saves gas. Nope. uint256. It’s the native word size of the EVM and cheaper when used alone. // This is optimal: uint256 public totalSupply;
// Not this: uint8 public totalSupply; // More expensive unless packed
